explained by another mental disorder","Episodes must occur weekly for at least one month"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecurrent unexpected panic attacks\u003C/strong\u003E are a core diagnostic criterion for panic disorder. A panic attack is characterised by an abrupt surge of intense fear or discomfort reaching a peak within minutes, during which at least four physical or cognitive symptoms occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe criterion that symptoms are \u003Cstrong\u003Enot attributable to physiological effects of a substance or another medical condition\u003C/strong\u003E is essential to ensure that symptoms are not better explained by medical conditions (such as thyroid disease) or substance use that can mimic panic attacks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESignificant maladaptive change in behaviour and worry about additional panic attacks\u003C/strong\u003E is also a diagnostic criterion. This often manifests as avoidance behaviours, such as avoiding situations where attacks have occurred or where help might not be available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe requirement that symptoms are \u003Cstrong\u003Enot better explained by another mental disorder\u003C/strong\u003E helps differentiate panic disorder from other conditions such as social anxiety disorder or specific phobias where panic attacks may occur in specific contexts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpisodes must occur weekly for at least one month\u003C/strong\u003E is NOT a diagnostic criterion for panic disorder. While panic attacks may occur frequently, there is no specific frequency requirement in the DSM-5 diagnostic criteria. The focus is instead on the presence of recurrent unexpected attacks and their impact on the person\u0027s functioning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis requires at least one month of persistent concern about having additional attacks or significant maladaptive changes in behaviour related to the attacks. The unexpected nature of the attacks distinguishes panic disorder from expected panic attacks that occur in response to specific feared situations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Panic disorder requires recurrent unexpected panic attacks with persistent concern about future attacks or maladaptive behaviour changes.","A panic attack requires at least 4 symptoms from a defined list, reaching peak intensity within 10 minutes.","Physical symptoms of panic attacks include palpitations, sweating, trembling, chest pain, and shortness of breath."],"references":["American Psychiatric Association, Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders 5ed, 2013"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67784"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19098"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67784"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T12:27:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T12:28:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11832"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82624"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7